value: Found solutions in which O had to make a direct forced choice in a defensive manner.
I just looked over it for awhile and I think he has two separate chances to win in that position which is better than everywhere else.
Tried various moves until I found something that created 2 win opportunities in one turn
I just played around with the xs and os until i found a wau for x to win but idk if it is the right way
starting at j9 forces O to defend at i9 and allows x to get 4 in a row with an opening at either end, meaning O has no chance

you have to force O in to a response action where each move that O makes is chosen by you. By using j9 as the first move O has to respond and play I9 in order to block the win. You then follow that move by playing in another spot that O has to defend the win. This allows you to place your 3rd X which gives you a line of 4 and a open spot on both sides so that he can no longer stop the win because you have two places that you could go in order to win the game.
I found a spot where there was open space to play around X's and kept trying out ideas.
As x, you also have to stop o from getting 5 in a row, and if you do not protect that corner, o will win in 2 moves.  It doesn't matter if x can win in 4, if o can win in 2
i needed to find a way to get 4 x's lined up, with an opening on either end to be able to ensure a win
Trying to get 5 in a row without letting 0 win before I could get X to win first
It had to be a strategy which kept the O's on the defensive, I had to have charge of both mine and their move.
using the first x move as my jump off point.. I tried to figure out where I could put the X's that the O's wouldn't be able to block.  I wasn't able to figure out the puzzle.
Position the first x in a position that will give multiple options to create 5 x's in a row.  This pushes the opponent into where they place their o and then you can manage the board.
It just looks like the best way to get 4 on the board.

My strategy was to keep trying different starting positions and see if I could win with X without allowing O to put me on the defensive.  However, it seemed the best I could do for X was to come out to a draw with just four moves.  O could force the early move with the lower three O spots and put the X on the defensive right away.  This seemed to limit the options and I couldn't figure a way around it.
